# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1-5-pentanediol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] In one industrial chemical synthesis, acetylene reacts with two equivalents of formaldehyde to form butyne-1,4-diol.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] Hydrogenation of butyne-1,4-diol gives butane-1,4-diol.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] It is also made on an industrial scale from maleic anhydride in the Davy process, which is first converted to the methyl maleate ester, then hydrogenated.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] Other routes are from butadiene, allyl acetate and succinic acid.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] A biological route to BD has been commercialized that uses a genetically modified organism.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] The biosynthesis proceeds via 4-hydroxybutyrate.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol is used industrially as a solvent and in the manufacture of some types of plastics, elastic fibers and polyurethanes.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] In organic chemistry, 1,4-butanediol is used for the synthesis of γ-butyrolactone (GBL).
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] In the presence of phosphoric acid and high temperature, it dehydrates to the important solvent tetrahydrofuran.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] At about 200 °C in the presence of soluble ruthenium catalysts, the diol undergoes dehydrogenation to form butyrolactone.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] It is used to synthesize 1,4-butanediol diglycidyl ether which is then used as a reactive diluent for epoxy resins.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] 1,4-Butanediol is used in the production of polybutylene terephthalate (PBT) plastic.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] World production of butane-1,4-diol was claimed to be about one million metric tons per year and market price is about US$2,000 (€1,600) per ton in 2005.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] In 2013, worldwide production was claimed to be billions of pounds (consistent with approximately one million metric tons).
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] Almost half of it is dehydrated to tetrahydrofuran to make fibers such as Spandex.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol is also used as a recreational drug known by some users as "Bute", "One Comma Four", "Liquid Fantasy", "One Four Bee" or "One Four B-D-O".
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] Some federal courts in the United States have stated that 1,4-butanediol exerts effects similar to its metabolite, GABA analogue gamma-hydroxybutyrate (GHB), but several other federal courts have ruled that it does not.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] 1,4-but***e***nediol (CAS 110-64-5) may be incorrectly sold as 1,4-butanediol but should not be confused with it.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol is rapidly converted into GHB acid by the enzymes alcohol dehydrogenase and aldehyde dehydrogenase, and differing levels of these enzymes may account for differences in effects and side effects between users.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] While co-administration of ethanol and GHB already poses serious risks, co-administration of ethanol with 1,4-butanediol will interact considerably and has many other potential risks.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] This is because the same enzymes that are responsible for metabolizing alcohol also metabolize 1,4-butanediol so there is a strong chance of a dangerous drug interaction.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol seems to have two types of pharmacological actions.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] The major psychoactive effects of 1,4-butanediol are because it is metabolized into GHB; however there is a study suggesting that 1,4-butanediol may have potential alcohol-like pharmacological effects on its own.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] The study arrived at this conclusion based on the finding that butane-1,4-diol coadministered with ethanol led to potentiation of some of the behavioral effects of ethanol.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] However, potentiation of ethanol's effects may simply be caused by competition for the alcohol dehydrogenase and aldehyde dehydrogenase enzymes with co-administered 1,4-butanediol.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] The shared metabolic rate-limiting steps thus leads to slowed metabolism and clearance for both compounds including ethanol's known toxic metabolite acetaldehyde.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] Another study found no effect following intracerebroventricular injection of butane-1,4-diol in rats.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] This contradicts the hypothesis of butane-1,4-diol having inherent alcohol-like pharmacological effects.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] Like gamma-hydroxybutyric acid, butane-1,4-diol is safe only in small amounts.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] Adverse effects in higher doses include nausea, vomiting, dizziness, sedation, vertigo, and potentially death if ingested in large amounts.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] Anxiolytic effects are diminished and side effects increased when used in combination with alcohol.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] While butane-1,4-diol is not currently scheduled federally in the United States, a number of states have classified 1,4-butanediol as a controlled substance.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] Individuals have been prosecuted for possession of 1,4-butanediol under the Federal Analog Act as substantially similar to GHB.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] A federal case in New York in 2002 ruled that 1,4-butanediol could not be considered an analog of GHB under federal law, but that decision was later overturned by the Second Circuit.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] A jury in Federal District Court in Chicago found that 1,4-butanediol was not an analog of GHB under federal law, which was not disputed on the case's appeal to the Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals, however this finding did not affect the outcome of the case.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] In the United Kingdom, 1,4-butanediol was scheduled in December 2009 (along with another GHB precursor, gamma-butyrolactone) as a Class C controlled substance.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] In Germany, the drug is not explicitly illegal, but might also be treated as illegal if used as a drug.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] It is controlled as a Schedule VI precursor in Canada.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] A toy called "Bindeez" ("Aqua Dots" in North America) was recalled by the distributor in November 2007 because of the presence of butane-1,4-diol.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] The toy consists of small beads that stick to each other by sprinkling water.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] The production plant seems to have intended to cut costs by replacing less toxic pentane-1,5-diol with butane-1,4-diol.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] ChemNet China listed the price of butane-1,4-diol at between about US$1,350–2,800 per metric ton, while the price for 1,5-pentanediol is about US$9,700 per metric ton.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] In August 2021, several people fell severely ill after consuming drinks at building L2.01 at the Lichtwiese Campus of Darmstadt Technical University, Germany.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] Seven showed severe symptoms, two were transported to a hospital in Frankfurt am Main, and a 30-year-old person was, for a time, in a critical state.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] Butane-1,4-diol had been detected in milk packages, as well as in water filters.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] At the location, detectives also found bromophenols and dicyclohexylamine.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] A variety of 1,4-butanediol derivatives are GHB-like drugs or GHB receptor agonists.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] These include GHB itself, γ-butyrolactone (GBL), aceburic acid, ethyl acetoxy butanoate (EAB), Γ-crotonolactone, γ-hydroxybutyraldehyde, γ-hydroxyvaleric acid (GHV), γ-valerolactone (GVL), γ-hydroxycrotonic acid (GHC or T-HCA), and 4-hydroxy-4-methylpentanoic acid (UMB68), among others.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-butanediol] An analogue that is not a 1,4-butanediol derivative but is related and still shows affinity for the GHB receptor is 3-chloropropanoic acid (UMB66).
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-pentadiene] In organic chemistry, **pentadiene** is any hydrocarbon with an open chain of five carbons, connected by two single bonds and two double bonds.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-pentadiene] All those compounds have the same molecular formula C5H8.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-pentadiene] Well known derivatives containing pentadiene groups include hexadienes, cyclopentadiene, and especially three fatty acids linoleic acid, α-linolenic acid, and arachidonic acid as well as their triglyceride esters (fats).
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-pentadiene] 1,4-Pentadiene can be prepared from 1,5-pentanediol via the diacetate.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-pentadiene] 1,3-Pentadiene, like 1,3-butadiene, undergoes a variety of cycloaddition reactions.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-pentadiene] For example, it forms a sulfolene upon treatment with sulfur dioxide.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-pentadiene] Methylene-interrupted polyenes are 1,4-pentadiene groups found in polyunsaturated fatty acids linoleic acid, α-linolenic acid, and arachidonic acid.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-pentadiene] These pentadiene derivatives are susceptible to lipid peroxidation, far moreso than monounsaturated or saturated fatty acids.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-pentadiene] The basis for this reactivity is the weakness of doubly allylic C-H bonds, leading to pentadienyl radicals.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-pentadiene] Products include fatty acid hydroperoxides, epoxy-hydroxy polyunsaturated fatty acids, jasmonates, divinylether fatty acids, and leaf aldehydes.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-pentadiene] Some of these derivatives are signalling molecules, some are used in plant defense (antifeedants), some are precursors to other metabolites that are used by the plant.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-pentadiene] Cyclooxygenases ("COX") are enzymes that generate prostanoids, including thromboxane and prostaglandins such as prostacyclin.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-pentadiene] Aspirin and ibuprofen exert their effects through inhibition of COX.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-pentadiene] Fats containing 1,4-pentadiene groups are drying oils, i.e. film-forming liquids suitable as paints.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-4-pentadiene] One practical consequence is that polyunsaturated fatty acids have poor shelf life owing to their tendency toward autoxidation, leading, in the case of edibles, to rancidification.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-5-pentanediol] 1,5-Pentanediol is produced by hydrogenation of glutaric acid and its derivatives.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-5-pentanediol] It can also be prepared by hydrogenolysis of tetrahydrofurfuryl alcohol.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-5-pentanediol] 1,4-Pentadiene can be prepared from 1,5-pentadiol via the diacetate.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-5-pentanediol] A toy called *Bindeez* (*Aqua Dots* in North America) was recalled by the distributor in November 2007 due to the unauthorized substitution of 1,5-pentanediol with 1,4-butanediol.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-5-pentanediol] The toy consists of small beads that stick to each other when sprinkled with water.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-5-pentanediol] 1,4-Butanediol, which when ingested is metabolized to gamma-hydroxybutyric acid, was detected by GC-MS.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/1-5-pentanediol] ChemNet China lists the price of 1,4-butanediol at between US$1,350–2,800/tonne, while the price for 1,5-pentanediol is about US$9,700/tonne.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] An **aqueous solution** is a solution in which the solvent is water.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] It is mostly shown in chemical equations by appending (aq) to the relevant chemical formula.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] For example, a solution of table salt, also known as sodium chloride (NaCl), in water would be represented as Na+(aq) + Cl−(aq).
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] The word *aqueous* (which comes from *aqua*) means pertaining to, related to, similar to, or dissolved in, water.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] As water is an excellent solvent and is also naturally abundant, it is a ubiquitous solvent in chemistry.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] Since water is frequently used as the solvent in experiments, the word solution refers to an aqueous solution, unless the solvent is specified.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] A *non-aqueous solution* is a solution in which the solvent is a liquid, but is not water.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] Substances that are *hydrophobic* ('water-fearing') do not dissolve well in water, whereas those that are *hydrophilic* ('water-loving') do.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] An example of a hydrophilic substance is sodium chloride.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] In an aqueous solution the hydrogen ions (H+) and hydroxide ions (OH−) are in Arrhenius balance ([H+] [OH−] = *Kw* = 1 × 10−14 at 298 K).
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] Acids and bases are aqueous solutions, as part of their Arrhenius definitions.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] An example of an Arrhenius acid is hydrogen chloride (HCl) because of its dissociation of the hydrogen ion when dissolved in water.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] Sodium hydroxide (NaOH) is an Arrhenius base because it dissociates the hydroxide ion when it is dissolved in water.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] Aqueous solutions may contain, especially in the alkaline zone or subjected to radiolysis, hydrated atomic hydrogen and hydrated electrons.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] Aqueous solutions that conduct electric current efficiently contain "strong" electrolytes, while those that conduct poorly are attributable to weaker electrolytes.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] The former substances are completely, or at least substantially, ionized in water; conversely, the weak electrolytes exhibit relatively limited ionization in water.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] The ability of ions to move freely through a solvent is a characteristic of an aqueous strong electrolyte solution; the solutes in a weaker electrolyte solution are present as ions, but only to a small degree.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] Non-electrolytes, conversely, are substances that dissolve in water, yet maintain their molecular integrity: they do not dissociate into ions.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] Examples include sugars, urea, glycerol, and ethanol.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] Reactions in aqueous solutions are usually metathesis reactions.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] Metathesis reactions are another term for double-displacement; that is, when a cation displaces to form an ionic bond with the other anion.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] The cation bonded with the latter anion will dissociate and bond with the other anion.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] A common metathesis reaction in aqueous solutions is a precipitation reaction.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] This reaction occurs when two aqueous strong electrolyte solutions mix and produce an insoluble solid, also known as a precipitate.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] The ability of a substance to dissolve in water is determined by whether the substance can match or exceed the strong attractive forces that water molecules generate between themselves.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] If the substance lacks the ability to dissolve in water, the molecules form a precipitate.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] When writing the equations of precipitation reactions, it is essential to determine the precipitate.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] To determine the precipitate, one must consult a chart of solubility.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] Soluble compounds are aqueous, while insoluble compounds are the precipitate.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] Complete ionic equations and net ionic equations are used to show dissociated ions in metathesis reactions.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/aqueous-solution] When performing calculations regarding the reacting of one or more aqueous solutions, in general one must know the concentration, or molarity, of the aqueous solutions.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] Since then, safer replacements have been marketed.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] Bindeez contains a craft kit that allows children to create various multi-dimensional designs using small colored beads.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] "Bindeez" can refer to either the toy itself or the small beads.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] The beads are arranged into various designs on a plastic tray.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] When the beads are sprayed with water, their surfaces become adhesive and they fuse together.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] The beads are then left to dry and the whole design becomes fixed and can be removed from the tray.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] Unlike iron-fusible beads, they do not require heat to be fused.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] The beads are approximately five millimetres in diameter and come in a wide range of colours.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] Bindeez are available in various different kits with accessories such as a drying fan, applicator pen, design templates for the beads, and water spray bottles.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] The product is labelled for ages four and above.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] Bindeez were first withdrawn from the Australian market, and subsequently from the North American market by the United States Consumer Product Safety Commission as well as European markets in early November 2007.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] They were recalled in Australia after a two-year-old boy and a 10-year-old girl became seriously ill after they swallowed large numbers of the beads and the connection between the illness and the product was discovered by a doctor at The Children's Hospital at Westmead, Sydney.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] Two children in North America became unconscious after similar ingestion.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] U.S. safety officials recalled about 4.2 million of the toys.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] The toy was supposed to contain the non-toxic plasticiser 1,5-pentanediol, but instead contained toxic 1,4-butanediol, which is metabolised into the sedative-hypnotic drug *gamma*-hydroxybutyric acid.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] At the time the substitution was discovered, the non-toxic ingredient was three to seven times more expensive than the toxic one.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] The affected children had seizure-like activity, which is an occasional side-effect of severe GHB overdose.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] Concern has been raised in the press that people may intentionally eat the beads in order to get high, potentially spawning a black market in the recalled toy.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] The issue was the topic of the second episode of the third season of *Elementary*, a Sherlock Holmes remake that aired on 6 November 2014.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] The episode was entitled "The Five Orange Pipz".
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] The murderer was attempting to market the beads after they would be released from evidence.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] A similar Japanese product, Aquabeads, which was developed in Japan by Epoch Co., and is produced by a different Chinese manufacturer, has not been recalled and is uncontaminated.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] In Australia, replacement beads were available from March 2008 onwards, based on the interim ban being lifted.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] The replacement beads will be manufactured using only approved ingredients.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] To discourage ingestion, the replacement beads will also be coated with the bitter-tasting substance known as Bitrex.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] The name of the product was also changed from Bindeez to Beados in an attempt to extinguish the link between the recall of the old toy and the new toy.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] In North America, the beads, previously marketed as "Aquadots", were remarketed as Pixos and marketed as "Safety Tested" in the television commercial as the commercial began hitting the airways in early July.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] However, the background music is exactly the same.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] In June 2009, "Chixos" featuring dolls began marketing more towards girls.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] Bindeez was awarded Australian "Toy of the Year" for 2007 prior to the recall.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] *Toy Wishes* magazine named it as one of the products among its 12 best toys of 2007.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] It is manufactured in China for the Australian-owned company Moose Enterprise P/L, and distributed in North America by Spin Master Ltd.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/bindeez] It is distributed in 40 countries, and 12 million packets, containing more than 8 billion beads, have been sold worldwide.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] The **boiling point** of a substance is the temperature at which the vapor pressure of a liquid equals the pressure surrounding the liquid and the liquid changes into a vapor.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] The boiling point of a liquid varies depending upon the surrounding environmental pressure.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] A liquid in a partial vacuum, i.e., under a lower pressure, has a lower boiling point than when that liquid is at atmospheric pressure.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Because of this, water boils at 100 °C, rounded from scientific precision of 99.97 °C (211.95 °F), under standard pressure at sea level, but at 93.4 °C (200.1 °F) at 1,905 metres (6,250 ft) altitude.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] For a given pressure, different liquids will boil at different temperatures.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] The **normal boiling point** (also called the **atmospheric boiling point** or the **atmospheric pressure boiling point**) of a liquid is the special case in which the vapor pressure of the liquid equals the defined atmospheric pressure at sea level, one atmosphere.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] At that temperature, the vapor pressure of the liquid becomes sufficient to overcome atmospheric pressure and allow bubbles of vapor to form inside the bulk of the liquid.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] The **standard boiling point** has been defined by IUPAC since 1982 as the temperature at which boiling occurs under a pressure of one bar.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] The heat of vaporization is the energy required to transform a given quantity (a mol, kg, pound, etc.) of a substance from a liquid into a gas at a given pressure (often atmospheric pressure).
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Liquids may change to a vapor at temperatures below their boiling points through the process of evaporation.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Evaporation is a surface phenomenon in which molecules located near the liquid's edge, not contained by enough liquid pressure on that side, escape into the surroundings as vapor.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] On the other hand, boiling is a process in which molecules anywhere in the liquid escape, resulting in the formation of vapor bubbles within the liquid.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] A *saturated liquid* contains as much thermal energy as it can without boiling (or conversely a *saturated vapor* contains as little thermal energy as it can without condensing).
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] If the pressure in a system remains constant (isobaric), a vapor at saturation temperature will begin to condense into its liquid phase as thermal energy (heat) is removed.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Similarly, a liquid at saturation temperature and pressure will boil into its vapor phase as additional thermal energy is applied.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] The boiling point corresponds to the temperature at which the vapor pressure of the liquid equals the surrounding environmental pressure.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Thus, the boiling point is dependent on the pressure.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Boiling points may be published with respect to the NIST, USA standard pressure of 101.325 kPa (1 atm), or the IUPAC standard pressure of 100.000 kPa (1 bar).
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] At higher elevations, where the atmospheric pressure is much lower, the boiling point is also lower.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] The boiling point increases with increased pressure up to the critical point, where the gas and liquid properties become identical.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] The boiling point cannot be increased beyond the critical point.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Likewise, the boiling point decreases with decreasing pressure until the triple point is reached.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] The boiling point cannot be reduced below the triple point.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] If the temperature in a system remains constant (an *isothermal* system), vapor at saturation pressure and temperature will begin to condense into its liquid phase as the system pressure is increased.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Similarly, a liquid at saturation pressure and temperature will tend to flash into its vapor phase as system pressure is decreased.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] There are two conventions regarding the *standard boiling point of water*: The *normal boiling point* is commonly given as 100 °C (212 °F) (actually 99.97 °C (211.9 °F) following the thermodynamic definition of the Celsius scale based on the kelvin) at a pressure of 1 atm (101.325 kPa).
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] The IUPAC-recommended *standard boiling point of water* at a standard pressure of 100 kPa (1 bar) is 99.61 °C (211.3 °F).
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] For comparison, on top of Mount Everest, at 8,848 m (29,029 ft) elevation, the pressure is about 34 kPa (255 Torr) and the boiling point of water is 71 °C (160 °F).
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] The Celsius temperature scale was defined until 1954 by two points: 0 °C being defined by the water freezing point and 100 °C being defined by the water boiling point at standard atmospheric pressure.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] The higher the vapor pressure of a liquid at a given temperature, the lower the normal boiling point (i.e., the boiling point at atmospheric pressure) of the liquid.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] The vapor pressure chart to the right has graphs of the vapor pressures versus temperatures for a variety of liquids.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] As can be seen in the chart, the liquids with the highest vapor pressures have the lowest normal boiling points.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] For example, at any given temperature, methyl chloride has the highest vapor pressure of any of the liquids in the chart.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] It also has the lowest normal boiling point (−24.2 °C), which is where the vapor pressure curve of methyl chloride (the blue line) intersects the horizontal pressure line of one atmosphere (atm) of absolute vapor pressure.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] The critical point of a liquid is the highest temperature (and pressure) it will actually boil at.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] The element with the lowest boiling point is helium.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Both the boiling points of rhenium and tungsten exceed 5000 K at standard pressure; because it is difficult to measure extreme temperatures precisely without bias, both have been cited in the literature as having the higher boiling point.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] As can be seen from the above plot of the logarithm of the vapor pressure vs. the temperature for any given pure chemical compound, its normal boiling point can serve as an indication of that compound's overall volatility.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] A given pure compound has only one normal boiling point, if any, and a compound's normal boiling point and melting point can serve as characteristic physical properties for that compound, listed in reference books.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] The higher a compound's normal boiling point, the less volatile that compound is overall, and conversely, the lower a compound's normal boiling point, the more volatile that compound is overall.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Some compounds decompose at higher temperatures before reaching their normal boiling point, or sometimes even their melting point.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] For a stable compound, the boiling point ranges from its triple point to its critical point, depending on the external pressure.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Beyond its triple point, a compound's normal boiling point, if any, is higher than its melting point.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Beyond the critical point, a compound's liquid and vapor phases merge into one phase, which may be called a superheated gas.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] At any given temperature, if a compound's normal boiling point is lower, then that compound will generally exist as a gas at atmospheric external pressure.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] If the compound's normal boiling point is higher, then that compound can exist as a liquid or solid at that given temperature at atmospheric external pressure, and will so exist in equilibrium with its vapor (if volatile) if its vapors are contained.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] If a compound's vapors are not contained, then some volatile compounds can eventually evaporate away in spite of their higher boiling points.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] In general, compounds with ionic bonds have high normal boiling points, if they do not decompose before reaching such high temperatures.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Many metals have high boiling points, but not all.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Very generally—with other factors being equal—in compounds with covalently bonded molecules, as the size of the molecule (or molecular mass) increases, the normal boiling point increases.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] When the molecular size becomes that of a macromolecule, polymer, or otherwise very large, the compound often decomposes at high temperature before the boiling point is reached.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Another factor that affects the normal boiling point of a compound is the polarity of its molecules.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] As the polarity of a compound's molecules increases, its normal boiling point increases, other factors being equal.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Closely related is the ability of a molecule to form hydrogen bonds (in the liquid state), which makes it harder for molecules to leave the liquid state and thus increases the normal boiling point of the compound.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Simple carboxylic acids dimerize by forming hydrogen bonds between molecules.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] A minor factor affecting boiling points is the shape of a molecule.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Making the shape of a molecule more compact tends to lower the normal boiling point slightly compared to an equivalent molecule with more surface area.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Most volatile compounds (anywhere near ambient temperatures) go through an intermediate liquid phase while warming up from a solid phase to eventually transform to a vapor phase.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] By comparison to boiling, a sublimation is a physical transformation in which a solid turns directly into vapor, which happens in a few select cases such as with carbon dioxide at atmospheric pressure.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] For such compounds, a sublimation point is a temperature at which a solid turning directly into vapor has a vapor pressure equal to the external pressure.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] In the preceding section, boiling points of pure compounds were covered.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Vapor pressures and boiling points of substances can be affected by the presence of dissolved impurities (solutes) or other miscible compounds, the degree of effect depending on the concentration of the impurities or other compounds.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] The presence of non-volatile impurities such as salts or compounds of a volatility far lower than the main component compound decreases its mole fraction and the solution's volatility, and thus raises the normal boiling point in proportion to the concentration of the solutes.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] This effect is called **boiling point elevation**.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] As a common example, salt water boils at a higher temperature than pure water.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] In other mixtures of miscible compounds (components), there may be two or more components of varying volatility, each having its own pure component boiling point at any given pressure.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] The presence of other volatile components in a mixture affects the vapor pressures and thus boiling points and dew points of all the components in the mixture.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] The dew point is a temperature at which a vapor condenses into a liquid.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Furthermore, at any given temperature, the composition of the vapor is different from the composition of the liquid in most such cases.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] In order to illustrate these effects between the volatile components in a mixture, a **boiling point diagram** is commonly used.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/boiling-point] Distillation is a process of boiling and [usually] condensation which takes advantage of these differences in composition between liquid and vapor phases.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] This registry includes all substances described since 1957, plus some substances from as far back as the early 1800s.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] It is a chemical database that includes organic and inorganic compounds, minerals, isotopes, alloys, mixtures, and nonstructurable materials (UVCBs - substances of **u**nknown or **v**ariable composition, **c**omplex reaction products, or **b**iological origin).
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] CAS RNs are generally serial numbers (with a check digit), so they do not contain any information about the structures themselves the way SMILES and InChI strings do.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] The CAS Registry is an authoritative collection of disclosed chemical substance information.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] It identifies more than 204 million unique organic and inorganic substances and 69 million protein and DNA sequences, plus additional information about each substance.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] It is updated with around 15,000 additional new substances daily.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] The full registry is available on a paid subscription basis.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] A collection of almost 500 thousand CAS registry numbers is made available under a CC BY-NC license at ACS Commons Chemistry.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] Historically, chemicals have been identified by a wide variety of synonyms and properties.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] One of the biggest challenges in the early development of substance indexing, a task undertaken by the Chemical Abstracts Service, was in identifying if a substance in literature was new or if it had been previously discovered.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] Well-known chemicals may be known via multiple generic, historical, commercial, and/or (black)-market names, and even systematic nomenclature based on structure alone was not universally useful.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] An algorithm was developed to translate the structural formula of a chemical into a computer-searchable table, which provided a basis for the service that listed each chemical with its CAS Registry Number, the CAS Chemical Registry System, which became operational in 1965.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] CAS Registry Numbers (CAS RN) are simple and regular, convenient for database searches.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] They offer a reliable, common and international link to every specific substance across the various nomenclatures and disciplines used by branches of science, industry, and regulatory bodies.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] Almost all molecule databases today allow searching by CAS Registry Number, and it is used as a global standard.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] A CAS Registry Number has no inherent meaning, but is assigned in sequential, increasing order when the substance is identified by CAS scientists for inclusion in the CAS Registry database.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] A CAS RN is separated by hyphens into three parts, the first consisting from two up to seven digits, the second consisting of two digits, and the third consisting of a single digit serving as a check digit.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] This format gives CAS a maximum capacity of 1,000,000,000 unique numbers.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] The check digit is found by taking the last digit times 1, the preceding digit times 2, the preceding digit times 3 etc., adding all these up and computing the sum modulo 10.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] The CAS Registry accepts entries that are (1) descriptive of matter consisting of chemical elements, (2) distinct from existing ones, and (3) present in scientific literature.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] The definition of "distinct" excludes different phases of the same substance (e.g. water and ice), but includes narrowing of existing concepts (e.g. carbon vs. graphite and diamond; isotope-labelled forms of an existing compound).
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] The Chemical Abstracts Service subscription includes an official search service.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] The Service ("CAS Data") provides information on the chemical itself, its mentions in published scholarly works and patents, curated biological and chemical reaction data, as well as listings of commercial sources and details on using a substance in a formulation.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/cas-registry-number] A subset of the registry can be accessed through the free-of-charge CAS Common Chemistry, which provides identifying information for the chemical in question.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] The database, originally known as StARlite, was developed by a biotechnology company called Inpharmatica Ltd. later acquired by Galapagos NV.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] The data was acquired for EMBL in 2008 with an award from The Wellcome Trust, resulting in the creation of the ChEMBL chemogenomics group at EMBL-EBI, led by John Overington.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] The ChEMBL database contains compound bioactivity data against drug targets.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] Bioactivity is reported in Ki, Kd, IC50, and EC50.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] Data can be filtered and analyzed to develop compound screening libraries for lead identification during drug discovery.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] ChEMBL version 2 (ChEMBL_02) was launched in January 2010, including 2.4 million bioassay measurements covering 622,824 compounds, including 24,000 natural products.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] This was obtained from curating over 34,000 publications across twelve medicinal chemistry journals.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] ChEMBL's coverage of available bioactivity data has grown to become "the most comprehensive ever seen in a public database.".
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] In October 2010 ChEMBL version 8 (ChEMBL_08) was launched, with over 2.97 million bioassay measurements covering 636,269 compounds.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] ChEMBL_10 saw the addition of the PubChem confirmatory assays, in order to integrate data that is comparable to the type and class of data contained within ChEMBL.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] ChEMBLdb can be accessed via a web interface or downloaded by File Transfer Protocol.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] It is formatted in a manner amenable to computerized data mining, and attempts to standardize activities between different publications, to enable comparative analysis.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] ChEMBL is also integrated into other large-scale chemistry resources, including PubChem and the ChemSpider system of the Royal Society of Chemistry.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] In addition to the database, the ChEMBL group have developed tools and resources for data mining.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] These include Kinase SARfari, an integrated chemogenomics workbench focussed on kinases.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] The system incorporates and links sequence, structure, compounds and screening data.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] GPCR SARfari is a similar workbench focused on GPCRs, and ChEMBL-Neglected Tropical Diseases (ChEMBL-NTD) is a repository for Open Access primary screening and medicinal chemistry data directed at endemic tropical diseases of the developing regions of the Africa, Asia, and the Americas.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] The primary purpose of ChEMBL-NTD is to provide a freely accessible and permanent archive and distribution centre for deposited data.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] July 2012 saw the release of a new malaria data service Archived 2016-07-30 at the Wayback Machine, sponsored by the Medicines for Malaria Venture (MMV), aimed at researchers around the globe.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] The data in this service includes compounds from the Malaria Box screening set, as well as the other donated malaria data found in ChEMBL-NTD.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] myChEMBL, the ChEMBL virtual machine, was released in October 2013 to allow users to access a complete and free, easy-to-install cheminformatics infrastructure.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] In December 2013, the operations of the SureChem patent informatics database were transferred to EMBL-EBI.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] In a portmanteau, SureChem was renamed SureChEMBL.
[src:1-5-pentanediol/chembl] 2014 saw the introduction of the new resource ADME SARfari - a tool for predicting and comparing cross-species ADME targets.
